There are three edges connecting $A$ to $B.$  We can choose any one of these edges to start with.  Suppose we start with the edge connecting $A$ to $B$ that runs parallel to the $x$-axis.

[asy]

size(4cm,4cm);

pair a1, b1, c1, d1;

a1=(1,1);
b1=(0,1);
c1=(1.6,1.4);
d1=(1,0);

pair e1, f1, g1, h1;

e1=(0,0);
f1=c1-(a1-d1);
g1=b1+(c1-a1);
h1=e1+(g1-b1);

draw(a1--d1--e1--b1--a1);
draw(b1--g1--c1--a1);
draw(c1--f1--d1);
draw(g1--h1--e1,dotted+1pt);
draw(h1--f1,dotted+1pt);

label("$A$",e1,SW);
label("$B$",c1,NE);
label("$1$",(a1+b1)/2,N);
label("$1$",(a1+d1)/2,E);
label("$1$",(b1+e1)/2,S);

[/asy]

Then there are two edges that we cannot use -- the edge connecting $A$ to $B$ that runs parallel to the $y$-axis, and the edge connecting $A$ to $B$ that runs parallel to the $z$-axis.

[asy]

size(4cm,4cm);

pair a1, b1, c1, d1;

a1=(1,1);
b1=(0,1);
c1=(1.6,1.4);
d1=(1,0);

pair e1, f1, g1, h1;

e1=(0,0);
f1=c1-(a1-d1);
g1=b1+(c1-a1);
h1=e1+(g1-b1);

draw(a1--d1--e1--b1--a1);
draw(b1--g1--c1--a1);
draw(c1--f1--d1);
draw(g1--h1--e1,dotted+1pt);
draw(h1--f1,dotted+1pt);

label("$A$",e1,SW);
label("$B$",c1,NE);
label("$1$",(a1+b1)/2,N);
label("$1$",(a1+d1)/2,E);
label("$1$",(b1+e1)/2,S);
draw((a1+b1)/2+(0,0.2)--(a1+d1)/2+(0,0.2),red,Arrow(size=9));
draw((a1+d1)/2+(0.2,0)--(b1+e1)/2+(0.2,0),red,Arrow(size=9));

[/asy]

This leaves us with only one edge to choose from.  Therefore, there is only $\boxed{1}$ such trip.

answer:
There are 9000 four-digit positive integers. For those without a 2 or 3, the first digit could be one of the seven numbers 1, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, or 9, and each of the other digits could be one of the eight numbers 0, 1, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, or 9. So there are \[
9000- 7\cdot 8\cdot 8\cdot 8=\boxed{5416}
\] four-digit numbers  with at least one digit that is a 2 or a 3.
